[An initial report on the FMD outbreak in Karashilik (was included in
Kazakhstan's immediate notification to the OIE of 22 Aug 2011 (see 20110823.2560). It stated, that the outbreak, caused by FMDV serotype
O, had started on 11 Aug 2011 and was confirmed 12 Aug 2011.
Reportedly, the susceptible animal population included 770 cattle and
2337 sheep. Clinical cases were seen only in cattle (33 cases),
without mortality. The number of destroyed cattle was said to be 69.
No explanation for this number was given. The notification further
said that vaccination, in response to the outbreak, was applied,
involving 735 cattle and 2337 sheep. The vaccine applied was,
reportedly, "polyvalent vaccine (A, O, C, SAT 1, SAT 2, and SAT 3)."
This unusual composition deserves to be explained.

Kazakhstan stopped vaccination against FMD in several of its provinces
in order to obtain the status of "free from FMD without vaccination",
enabling exports of live cattle and/or beef. During 2010, large areas
such as Akmolah, Pavlodar and Northern Kazakhstan remained
unvaccinated.

For the location of Karashilik see
http://healthmap.org/r/1a1v and
http://www.fallingrain.com/world/KZ/15/Karashilik.html. According to
the latter, Karashilik is situated 130 km (80 miles) north east to the
Semipalatinsk Nuclear Test Site. - Mod.AS]
